<div class="row">
  <div class="twelve column">
    <h3>Icons and their Meanings</h3>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="row">
  <div class="four columns justify">
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span class="icon merge">Merge</span> - This is the "Merge" icon.
          It stays <strong class="pending">red</strong> until the PR receives at least 3
          "shipit" emojis (:+1: or :shipit:). When it is ready to be merge,
          this icon will be <strong class="ready">green</strong>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div class="four columns justify">
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
        <span class="icon review">Review</span> - This is the "Reviewed" icon.
          It stays <strong class="pending">red</strong> until you have commented
          on the thread issue of GitHub with a "shipit" emojis (:+1: or :shipit:).
          It turns <strong class="ready">green</strong> after you have reviewed it.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div class="four columns justify">
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span class="icon comment">Comment</span> - This is the "Commented" icon.
          It stays <strong class="pending">red</strong> until you have commented
          on the thread pull request of GitHub. It turns <strong class="ready">green</strong>
          after you commented on the PR. When the author pushes more commits and/or
          updates the PR, this icon goes back to <strong class="pending">red</strong>
          until you make new comments on the PR thread. This is ideal for PRs not
          ready to merge that you need to keep checking for modifications.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

